68","1433–1513":"1433–1513","1411–1476":"1411–1476","1513":"1513","1468":"1468","1411":"1411","1433":"1433","1476":"1476","1487":"1487","about 1411":"about 1411","about 1433":"about 1433","about 1432":"about 1432","1407":"1407","after 1476":"after 1476","1427":"1427","Hatherton, Cheshire, England":"Hatherton, Cheshire, England","Prescot, Lancashire, England":"Prescot, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Corbet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Corbett  .","History: Walter Corbet, a royal knight in 12th-century Scotland, was the first of that name in that kingdom. His 13th-century descendants were major landholders in the Borders, and in the 14th century they acquired lands in the North of Scotland."],"variants":[{"name":"Corbett","meanings":["English (West Midlands, of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>corbet</i> ‘raven’, probably denoting someone with dark hair or a dark complexion.","History: This is the name of a family descended from Hugh <i>Corbet</i>, a Norman baron who settled in Shropshire following the Norman Conquest. One of his descendants, Sir Richard Corbet, was granted land near Shrewsbury in 1223; since the 13th century, this place has been known as Moreton Corbet. The name was taken from Shropshire to Scotland in the 12th century and to northern Ireland in the 17th century, and thence to North America by at least one group of bearers of the name."]}]},{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Cecilia Corbet was born about 1411, in Hatherton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Robert Corbet II about 1432, in Hatherton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died after 1476, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1411–after 1476":"umbes 1411–pärast 1476","1407–1487":"1407–1487","1427–1468":"1427–1468","1433–1513":"1433–1513","1411–1476":"1411–1476","1513":"1513","1468":"1468","1411":"1411","1433":"1433","1476":"1476","1487":"1487","about 1411":"umbes 1411","about 1433":"umbes 1433","about 1432":"umbes 1432","1407":"1407","after 1476":"pärast 1476","1427":"1427","Hatherton, Cheshire, England":"Hatherton, Cheshire, England","Prescot, Lancashire, England":"Prescot, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1411–after 1476":"noin 1411–1476 jälkeen","1407–1487":"1407–1487","1427–1468":"1427–1468","1433–1513":"1433–1513","1411–1476":"1411–1476","1513":"1513","1468":"1468","1411":"1411","1433":"1433","1476":"1476","1487":"1487","about 1411":"noin 1411","about 1433":"noin 1433","about 1432":"noin 1432","1407":"1407","after 1476":"1476 jälkeen","14